RPE Cheat Sheet – Forge of Olympus
What is RPE?
RPE = Rating of Perceived Exertion.
It’s a subjective score (usually 1–10) of how hard a set felt.

RPE 10 – Absolutely maximal. Cannot do another rep, even if threatened.

RPE 9 – Very hard. Could maybe do one more rep, but it would be a grind.

RPE 8 – Hard but manageable. Could definitely do two more reps.

RPE 7 – Moderate. Could do three more reps with good form.

RPE 6 – Light. Could do four more reps.

RPE depends on how you feel – not just the number of reps left. A slow, grinding rep at RPE 8 might feel worse than fast, smooth reps at RPE 8.

What is RIR?
RIR = Reps in Reserve.
It’s a more objective count of how many more reps you could have performed with perfect form.

RIR 0 – No reps left. You physically cannot do another rep.

RIR 1 – Exactly 1 rep left.

RIR 2 – 2 reps left.

RIR 3 – 3 reps left.

RIR is easier for beginners to estimate, while advanced lifters often prefer RPE because it incorporates form breakdown and fatigue.

How RPE and RIR are related (but not the same)
In many programs, they are used interchangeably with a simple approximation:

RPE	Approx. RIR
10	0
9	1
8	2
7	3
6	4
But this is only a rule of thumb.
RPE can be influenced by:

Rep speed (a slow rep at RPE 8 might feel like RPE 9)

Mental state (stress makes the same weight feel harder)

Discomfort or pain

The app uses your logged RPE to adjust next session’s weights, not a fixed formula. That’s what makes it adaptive.

Why RPE (and RIR) beat fixed percentages
Fixed percentages ignore how you feel today.

RPE/RIR accounts for sleep, recovery, stress, and soreness.

The app learns from your performance – if you over‑ or under‑shoot, the next session corrects automatically.

Common mistakes (and how the app fixes them)
Mistake	App solution
“I think I had one more rep” – you log RPE 9	The app treats it as 1 RIR (approx.) and adjusts next weight.
“I went too heavy on a bad day”	Session readiness lowers target RPE automatically.
“I have no idea what weight to use”	The app calculates it from your previous 1RM or logged weights.
“My progress stalled”	The app increases weight when you hit RPE targets consistently.
